# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bevy-ecs-rust
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/data-oriented-design] In computing, **data-oriented design** is a program optimization approach motivated by efficient usage of the CPU cache, often used in video game development.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/data-oriented-design] The approach is to focus on the data layout, separating and sorting fields according to when they are needed, and to think about transformations of data.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/data-oriented-design] Proponents include Mike Acton, Scott Meyers, and Jonathan Blow.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/data-oriented-design] The parallel array (or structure of arrays) is the main example of data-oriented design.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/data-oriented-design] It is contrasted with the *array of structures* typical of object-oriented designs.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/data-oriented-design] The definition of data-oriented design as a programming paradigm can be seen as contentious as many believe that it can be used side by side with another paradigm, but due to the emphasis on data layout, it is also incompatible with most other paradigms.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/data-oriented-design] These methods became especially popular in the mid to late 2000s during the seventh generation of video game consoles that included the IBM PowerPC based PlayStation 3 (PS3) and Xbox 360 consoles.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/data-oriented-design] Historically, game consoles often have relatively weak central processing units (CPUs) compared to the top-of-line desktop computer counterparts.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/data-oriented-design] This is a design choice to devote more power and transistor budget to the graphics processing units (GPUs).
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/data-oriented-design] For example, the 7th generation CPUs were not manufactured with modern out-of-order execution processors, but instead use in-order processors with high clock speeds and deep pipelines.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/data-oriented-design] In addition, most types of computing systems have main memory located hundreds of clock cycles away from the processing elements.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/data-oriented-design] Furthermore, as CPUs have become faster alongside a large increase in main memory capacity, there is massive data consumption that increases the likelihood of cache misses in the shared bus, otherwise known as Von Neumann bottlenecking.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/data-oriented-design] Consequently, locality of reference methods have been used to control performance, requiring improvement of memory access patterns to fix bottlenecking.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/data-oriented-design] Some of the software issues were also similar to those encountered on the Itanium, requiring loop unrolling for upfront scheduling.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/data-oriented-design] The claim is that traditional object-oriented programming (OOP) design principles result in poor data locality, more so if runtime polymorphism (dynamic dispatch) is used (which is especially problematic on some processors).
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/data-oriented-design] Although OOP appears to "organise code around data", it actually organises source code around data types rather than physically grouping individual fields and arrays in an efficient format for access by specific functions.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/data-oriented-design] Moreover, it often hides layout details under abstraction layers, while a data-oriented programmer wants to consider this first and foremost.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] ECS prioritizes composition over inheritance.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] Every entity is defined not by a type hierarchy, but by the components associated with it.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] Systems act globally over all entities that have the required components.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] For example, a food system might iterate through every entity with a relevant component tracking hunger, and act on them to push them a little away from satiation at time intervals.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] Entities lacking the component like terrain or items would be naturally ignored by the food system.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] Due to an ambiguity in the English language, an interpretation of the name is that an ECS is a system comprising entities and components.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] In the 2002 talk at GDC, Scott Bilas compared a C++ object system and his new custom component system.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] This is consistent with a traditional use of *system* terms in general systems engineering with Common Lisp Object System and type system as examples.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] Although mostly found in video game development, the ECS can be useful in other domains, such as in robotics simulators like Gazebo.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] ECS combines orthogonal, well-established ideas in general computer science and programming language theory.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] For example, components can be seen as a mixin idiom in various programming languages.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] Components are a specialized case under the general delegation approach and meta-object protocol.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] That is, any complete component object system can be expressed with the *templates* and *empathy* model within The Orlando Treaty vision of object-oriented programming.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] An entity represents a general-purpose object.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] In a game engine context, for example, every coarse game object is represented as an entity.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] Usually, it only consists of a unique ID.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] as possessing a particular aspect, and (the component) holds the data needed to model that aspect.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] For example, every game object that can take damage might have a Health component associated with its entity.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] A system is a process that acts on all entities with the desired components.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] For example, a physics system may query for entities having mass, velocity and position components, iterate over the results, and do physics calculations for each entity using the set of components.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] The behavior of an entity can be changed at runtime by systems that add, remove or modify components.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] This eliminates the ambiguity problems of deep and wide inheritance hierarchies often found in object-oriented programming techniques that are difficult to understand, maintain, and extend.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] Common ECS approaches are highly compatible with, and are often combined with, data-oriented design techniques.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] Data for all instances of a component are contiguously stored together in physical memory, enabling efficient memory access for systems that operate over many entities.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] In 1963, Ivan Sutherland's Sketchpad stored the visual elements of a drawing using an early form of an ECS.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] Instead of encapsulating points in different objects (e.g. lines, circles, rectangles) points were stored in a ring buffer, and visual elements were only referencing them.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] When moving a point, this allowed updating all the shapes and constraints using it.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] In 1998, *Thief: The Dark Project* pioneered an ECS.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] The engine was later used for its sequel, as well as *System Shock 2*.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] In 2002, Scott Bilas of Gas Powered Games (Dungeon Siege) gave a seminal talk on ECS.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] This inspired numerous later well-known implementations.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] In early January 2007, Mick West who worked on the Tony Hawk series, shared his experiences on the process of ECS adoption at Neversoft.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] Also in 2007, the team working on *Operation Flashpoint: Dragon Rising* experimented with ECS designs, including those inspired by Bilas/*Dungeon Siege*, and Adam Martin later wrote a detailed account of ECS design, including definitions of core terminology and concepts.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] In particular, Martin's work popularized the ideas of systems as a first-class element, entities as identifiers, components as raw data, and code stored in systems, not in components or entities.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] In 2015, Apple Inc. introduced GameplayKit, an API framework for iOS, macOS and tvOS game development that includes an implementation of ECS.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] In October 2018 the company Unity released its megacity demo that utilized a tech stack built on an ECS.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] Unity's ECS runs on a powerful optimized architecture known as DOTS, which "empowers creators to scale processing in a highly performant manner".
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] The data layout of different ECS's can differ as well as the definition of components, how they relate to entities, and how systems access entities' components.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] Adam Martin defines in his blog series what he considers an Entity–Component–System.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] An entity only consists of an ID for accessing components.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] It is a common practice to use a unique ID for each entity.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] Some of these advantages can also be achieved using smart pointers.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] Components have no game code (behavior) inside of them.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] The components don't have to be located physically together with the entity, but should be easy to find and access using the entity.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] Unity's layout has tables, each with columns of components.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] In this system an entity *type* is based on the components it holds.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] For every entity *type* there is a table (called an *archetype*) holding columns of components that match the components used in the entity.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] To access a particular entity one must find the correct archetype (table) and index into each column to get each corresponding component for that entity.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] The normal way to transmit data between systems is to store the data in components, and then have each system access the component sequentially.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] For example, the position of an object can be updated regularly.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] This position is then used by other systems.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] If there are a lot of different infrequent events, a lot of flags will be needed in one or more components.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] Systems will then have to monitor these flags every iteration, which can become inefficient.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] A solution could be to use the observer pattern.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] All systems that depend on an event subscribe to it.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] The action from the event will thus only be executed once, when it happens, and no polling is needed.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] The ECS has no trouble with dependency problems commonly found in object-oriented programming since components are simple data buckets and have no dependencies.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] Each system will typically query the set of components an entity must have for the system to operate on it.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] For example, a render system might register the model, transformations, and drawable components.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] When it runs, the system will perform its logic on any entity that has all of those components.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] Other entities are simply skipped, with no need for complex dependency trees.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] However, this can be a place for bugs to hide, since propagating values from one system to another through components may be hard to debug.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] ECS may be used where uncoupled data needs to be bound to a given lifetime.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] The ECS uses composition, rather than inheritance trees.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] An entity will be typically made up of an ID and a list of components that are attached to it.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] Any game object can be created by adding the correct components to an entity.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] This allows the developer to easily add features to an entity, without any dependency issues.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] For example, a player entity could have a *bullet* component added to it, which would then meet the requirements to be manipulated by some *bulletHandler* system, which then could result in that bullet doing damage to other objects by running into them.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] The merits of using ECS for storing the game state have been proclaimed by many game developers like Adam Martin.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/entity-component-system] One good example is the blog posts by Richard Lord, where he discusses the merits and why ECS-designed game data storage systems are so useful.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] A **game engine** is a software framework primarily designed for video game development, which may include specialized software libraries and packages, such as level editors.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] The term "engine" is a direct analogue of "software engine", having it employed across sectors of the software industry.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] Furthermore, *game engine* may also refer to the integrated development environment as an interface behind the given framework, typically a suite of visual development tools and features for developing video games.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] Game developers can use game engines to create and publish video games across platforms, such as desktops, mobile devices, video game consoles, and other types of computers.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] The core functionalities commonly covered by a game engine are a 2D or 3D renderer, physics engine, audio engine, scripting, animation, artificial intelligence, networking, streaming, memory management, threads, localization support, scene graph, and cinematics.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] Game engine developers often economize game development through reuse or adaptation of abstractions built into game engines for production of various games, or through porting of videogames from a single to other target platforms.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] In many cases, game engines provide a suite of visual development tools in addition to reusable software components.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] These tools are generally provided in an integrated development environment to enable simplified, rapid development of games in a data-driven manner.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] Game-engine developers often attempt to preempt implementer needs by developing robust software suites, which include many elements a game developer may need to build a game.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] Most game-engine suites provide facilities that ease development, such as graphics, sound, physics and artificial intelligence (AI) functions.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] Like other types of middleware, game engines usually provide platform abstraction, allowing the same game to run on various platforms (including game consoles and personal computers) with few, if any, changes made to the game source code.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] Often, programmers design game engines with a component-based architecture that allows specific systems in the engine to be replaced or extended with more specialized (and often more expensive) game-middleware components.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] Some game engines comprise a series of loosely-connected game middleware components that can be selectively combined to create a custom engine, instead of the more common approach of extending or customizing a flexible integrated product.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] However achieved, extensibility remains a high priority for game engines due to the wide variety of uses for which they are applied.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] Despite the specificity of the name "game engine", end users often re-purpose game engines for other kinds of interactive applications with real-time graphical requirements—such as marketing demos, architectural visualizations, training simulations, and modeling environments.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] Some game engines only provide real-time 3D rendering capabilities instead of the wide range of functionality needed by games.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] These engines rely upon the game developer to implement the rest of this functionality or to assemble it from other game-middleware components.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] These types of engines are generally referred to as a "graphics engine", "rendering engine", or "3D engine" instead of the all-encompassing term "game engine".
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] This terminology is inconsistently used, as many full-featured 3D game engines are simply referred to as "3D engines".
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] Examples of graphics engines include: Crystal Space, Genesis3D, Irrlicht, OGRE, RealmForge, Truevision3D, and Vision Engine.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] Modern game- or graphics-engines generally provide a scene graph—an object-oriented representation of the 3D game-world which often simplifies game design and can be used for more efficient rendering of vast virtual worlds.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] Most game engines or graphics engines use a Graphics API, which eases communication with the GPU.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] But older games did not have hardware acceleration or GPUs and had to build their own software renderer.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] As technology ages, the components of an engine may become obsolete or insufficient for the requirements of a given project.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] Since the complexity of programming an entirely new engine may result in unwanted delays (or necessitate that a project restart from the beginning), an engine-development team may elect to update their existing engine with newer functionality or components.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] Game engines are not limited to use in the video game field, and have found uses in other scientific fields.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] Part of this is due to game engines being optimized for consumer-grade computing equipment rather than high-performance computing, allowing researchers to develop programs for their use on lower cost machines.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] Game engines also simplify many of the computing operations needed for scientific software, including graphics, networking, and interactivity, reducing the need to develop these features themselves.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] Before game engines, games were typically written as singular entities: a game for the Atari 2600, for example, had to be designed from the bottom up to make optimal use of the display hardware—this core display routine is now called the kernel by developers of games for older systems.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] Other platforms had more leeway, but even when display was not a concern, memory constraints usually sabotaged attempts to create the data-heavy design that an engine needs.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] Even on more accommodating platforms, very little could be reused between games.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] The rapid advance of arcade hardware—which was the leading edge of the market at the time—meant that most of the code would have to be thrown out afterwards anyway, as later generations of games would use completely different game designs that took advantage of extra resources.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] Thus, most game designs through the 1980s were designed through a hard-coded rule set with a small number of levels and graphics data.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] Since the golden age of arcade video games, it became common for video game companies to develop in-house game engines for use with first-party software.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] A notable example of an in-house game engine on home consoles in the mid-1980s was the smooth side-scrolling engine developed by Shigeru Miyamoto's team at Nintendo for the Nintendo Entertainment System (NES).
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] The engine they had developed for the side-scrolling racing game *Excitebike* (1984) was later employed for the scrolling platformer *Super Mario Bros.* (1985).
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] This allowed Mario to smoothly accelerate from a walk to a run, rather than move at a constant speed like in earlier platformers.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] While third-party game engines were not common until the rise of 3D computer graphics in the 1990s, several 2D game creation systems were produced in the 1980s for independent video game development.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] Klik & Play (1994) is another legacy offering that is still available.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] The term *game engine* emerged in the mid-1990s, particularly with the rise of 3D games like first-person shooters, which often featured a dedicated first-person shooter engine.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] For instance, Epic Games, founded by Tim Sweeney, debuted its Unreal Engine in 1998.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] Later games, such as id Software's *Quake III Arena* and Epic Games' *Unreal* (1998), were designed with this approach in mind, with the engine and content developed separately.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] At the very least, reusable engines make developing game sequels faster and easier, which is a valuable advantage in the competitive video game industry.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] While a strong rivalry existed between Epic Games and id Software around 2000, Epic Game's Unreal Engine has since become far more popular than id Tech 4 and its successor, id Tech 5.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] Modern game engines are some of the most complex applications written, often featuring dozens of finely-tuned systems interacting to ensure a precisely-controlled user experience.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] The continued evolution of game engines has created a strong separation between rendering, scripting, artwork, and level design.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] As such, it is now common, for example, for a typical game development team to have several times as many artists as actual programmers.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] While third-party game engines are predominantly used in the development of first-person shooter games, they are also being used across other genres.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] For example, Gamebryo is used in *The Elder Scrolls III: Morrowind* and *Dark Age of Camelot*, whereas Unreal Engine 2 is used in *Lineage II*.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] Game engines are also used for games originally developed for home consoles, with RenderWare for the *Grand Theft Auto* and *Burnout* franchises as an example.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] Due to modern multi-core systems and growing demands in realism, exploiting threads has become more important.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] Separate threads of execution within a game engine manage intensive operations, including rendering, asset streaming, audio playback, and physics simulation.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] Racing games have typically been at the forefront of threading with the physics engine running in a separate thread long before other core subsystems were moved, partly because rendering and related tasks need updating at only 30–60 Hz.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] For example, on PlayStation 3, physics ran in *Need For Speed* at 100 Hz, versus *Forza Motorsport 2* at 360 Hz.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] Although the term was first used in the 1990s, few earlier systems in 1980s are considered as game engines, such as Sierra's Adventure Game Interpreter (AGI) and SCI systems, LucasArts' SCUMM system and Incentive Software's Freescape engine (in 1986).
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] Unlike most modern game engines, these game engines were never used in any third-party products (except for the SCUMM system, which was licensed to and used by Humongous Entertainment).
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] As game engine technology matures and becomes more user friendly, the application of game engines has widened in scope.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] They are now used for serious games: visualization, training, medical, and military simulation applications, with the CryEngine being one example.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] To improve accessibility, new hardware platforms are also now targeted by game engines, including mobile phones (e.g.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] Additionally, more game engines are being built upon higher-level languages, such as Java, C# and .NET (e.g., TorqueX, and Visual3D.NET), Python (Panda3D), or Lua Script (Leadwerks).
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] As most 3D-rich games are now mostly limited by the power of a graphics card, the potential slowdown due to translation overheads of higher-level languages becomes negligible, while productivity gains offered by these languages serve the game engine developers' benefit.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] These recent trends are being propelled by companies such as Microsoft to support indie game development.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] Microsoft developed XNA as the primary Software Development Kit (SDK) for all video games released on Xbox and their related products.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] This includes the Xbox Live Indie Games channel designed specifically for smaller developers who do not have the extensive resources necessary to box games for sale on retail shelves.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] It is becoming easier and cheaper than ever to develop game engines for platforms that support managed frameworks.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] Producers of game engines decide how they allow users to use their products.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] Just as gaming is an industry, so are the engines they are built off.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] The major game engines come at varying prices, whether it be in the form of subscription fees or license payments.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] Unity and Unreal Engine are currently the two most popular choices for game developers.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] Although the differences among the different game engines blur as they build their own tools on top of them, different game developers may be too used to a system to change, or attracted by the huge benefits of such engines regardless of pay-walls.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] Free and open-source engines such as Godot, have seen a rise in popularity, particularly following the 2023 Unity pricing controversy which drove game developers and studios to seek engines with a permissive license.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] Applied more broadly, game engines themselves can be described as middleware.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] In video games, however, *middleware* is often used to refer to subsystems of functionality within a game engine.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] Some game middleware does only one thing, yet does it more convincingly or more efficiently than general purpose middleware.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] The four most-widely used middleware packages that provide subsystems of functionality include RAD Game Tools' Bink, Firelight FMOD, Havok, and Scaleform GFx.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] RAD Game Tools develops Bink for basic video rendering, along with Miles audio, and Granny 3D rendering.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] Firelight FMOD is a low cost robust audio library and toolset.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] Havok provides a robust physics simulation system, along with a suite of animation and behavior applications.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] Scaleform provides GFx for high performance Flash UI and high-quality video playback, and an Input Method Editor (IME) addon for in-game Asian chat support.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] Other middleware is used for performance optimization—for example Simplygon helps to optimize and generate level of detail meshes, and Umbra adds occlusion culling optimizations to 3D graphics.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] Some middleware contains full source code, or is provided an API reference for a compiled binary library.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-engine] Some middleware programs can be licensed either way, usually for a higher fee for full source code.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Professional game development usually begins with a game design, which itself has several possible origins.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Occasionally the game development process starts with no clear design in mind, but as a series of experiments.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] For example, game designer Will Wright began development of *The Sims* by getting programmers to experiment with several ideas.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Programmers are often required to produce prototypes of gameplay ideas and features.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] A great deal of prototyping may take place during pre-production, before the design document is complete, and may help determine what features the design specifies.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Prototypes are developed quickly with very little time for up-front design and mostly act as a proof of concept or to test ideas.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] They are not expected to work flawlessly, but are developed to try out new, sometimes exotic, ideas.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Though the programmer's main job is not to develop the game design, the programmers often contribute to the design, as do game artists.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] The game designer will solicit input from both the producer and the art and programming lead for ideas and strategies for the game design.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Often individuals in non-lead positions also contribute, such as copywriters and other programmers and artists.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Programmers often closely follow the game design document.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] As the game development progresses, the design document changes as programming limitations and new capabilities are discovered and exploited.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] During production, programmers may create a great deal of source code to create the game described in the game's design document.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Along the way, the design document is modified to meet limitations or expanded to exploit new features.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] The design document is very much a "living document", much of whose life is dictated by programmer's schedules, talent and resourcefulness.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] While many programmers have some say in a game's content, most game producers solicit input from the lead programmer as to the status of a game programming development.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] The lead is responsible for knowing the status of all facets of the game's programming and for pointing out limitations.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] The lead programmer may also pass on suggestions from the programmers as to possible features they'd like to implement.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] With today's visually rich content, the programmer must often interact with the art staff.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] This very much depends on the programmer's role, of course.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] For example, a 3D graphics programmer may need to work side by side with the game's 3D modelers discussing strategies and design considerations, while an AI programmer may need to interact very little, if at all, with the art staff.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] To help artists and level designers with their tasks, programmers may volunteer or be called upon to develop tools and utilities.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Many of these may be for a specific purpose and can be buggy due to time constraints (time for development of such tools is often not included in a game's schedule) as well as because they are only for in-house use anyway.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Many game tools are developed in RAD languages for quicker development and may be discarded after the completion of the game.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] The formal quality assurance testing process, performed by professional game testers, begins well into game development.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] High-budget titles may begin testing with the first playable alpha, while low-budget and casual games might not enter testing until a release candidate is ready.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] The programmers' task is to fix errors and bugs as such are discovered by the QA teams.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Final tasks include "polishing" the game, such as programmers fixing occasional bugs—from minor to catastrophic—that may arise during the last phases of testing.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Game developers may have a beta testing period, but the definition of such varies from developer to developer.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Often a beta contains all of the game's features, but may have a few bugs or incomplete content.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Few games are given a public beta period, for example, to measure stress tolerance for game servers.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] When the game is deemed complete, it is said to have "gone gold" and is shipped off to the publisher.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Depending on circumstances, the publisher may then subject it to its own quality assurance or may begin pressing the game from the gold master.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Once a game ships, the maintenance phase for the video game begins.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Programmers wait for a period to get as many bug reports as possible.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Once the developer thinks they've obtained enough feedback, the programmers start working on a patch.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] The patch may take weeks or months to develop, but it's intended to fix most bugs and problems with the game.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Occasionally a patch may include extra features or content or may even alter gameplay.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Most modern games take from one to three years to complete.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] The length of development depends on a number of factors, but programming is required throughout all phases of development except the very early stages of game design.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Like other software, game development programs are generated from source code to the actual program (called the *executable*) by a compiler.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Source code can be developed with almost any text editor, but many professional game programmers use a full integrated development environment.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Once again, which IDE one uses depends on the target platform.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] In addition to IDEs, many game development companies create custom tools developed to be used in-house.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Some of these include prototypes and asset conversion tools (programs that change artwork, for example, into the game's custom format).
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Some custom tools may even be delivered with the game, such as a level editor.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Game development companies are often very willing to spend thousands of dollars to make sure their programmers are well equipped with the best tools.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] A well outfitted programmer may have two to three development systems and multiple monitors dominating their office or cubicle.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Once the game's initial design has been agreed upon, the development language must be decided upon.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] The choice depends upon many factors, such as language familiarity of the programming staff, target platforms, the execution speed requirements and the language of any game engines, APIs or libraries being used.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] For personal computers, the language selected may be little more than a matter of preference.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Language bindings for popular libraries such as SDL and Allegro are widespread, and the performance gap between idiomatic code written in modern compiled languages is negligible.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] The most popular languages are usually procedural or object-oriented and implemented via compilers; for example, C, C++, and Java.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] However, developers may take into account domain-specific features, such as interfacing with the operating system, and resilience to reverse engineering for online video games.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Many games are not written in one language exclusively, and may combine two or more languages; For example, Unity, a popular game engine, has different pieces written in C, C++, and C#.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] For consoles, the support of the target platform is usually the most considered factor.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] In the past, video games for consoles were written almost exclusively in assembly due to limited resources in terms of both storage and processing speed.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] However, as technology has advanced, so have the options for game development on consoles.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Nintendo, Microsoft, and Sony all have differing SDKs for their Nintendo Switch, Xbox One, and PlayStation 4 consoles, respectively.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] High-level scripting languages are increasingly being used as embedded extensions to the underlying game written in a compiled programming language, for the convenience of both the original developer and anyone who would wish to mod the game.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Lua is a very popular choice, as its API is written in ANSI C and the language is designed to be embedded into other applications.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Many developers have created custom languages altogether for their games, such as id Software's QuakeC and Epic Games' UnrealScript.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] A key decision in game programming is which, if any, APIs and libraries to use.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Today, there are numerous libraries available which take care of key tasks of game programming.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Some libraries can handle sound processing, input, and graphics rendering.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Some can even handle some AI tasks such as pathfinding.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] There are even entire game engines that handle most of the tasks of game programming and only require coding game logic.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Which APIs and libraries one chooses depends largely on the target platform.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] For example, libraries for PlayStation 2 development may not be available for Microsoft Windows and vice versa.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] However, there are game frameworks available that allow or ease cross-platform development, so programmers can program a game in a single language and have the game run on several platforms, such as the Wii, PlayStation 3, Xbox 360, PSP and Microsoft Windows.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Today, graphics are a key defining feature of most games.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] While 2D graphics used to be the norm for games released through the mid-1990s, most AAA games now boast full 3D graphics, even for games which are largely 2D in nature, such as *Civilization III*.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] However, purely 2D graphics have experienced a Renaissance with indie games.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] A well established personal computer platform is Microsoft Windows.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Since it came pre-installed on almost ninety percent of PCs sold, it now has the largest user base.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] The two most popular 3D graphics APIs for Microsoft Windows are Direct3D and OpenGL.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] The benefits and weaknesses of each API are hotly debated among Windows game programmers.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Currently, the most popular Computing platform is Google Android.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Since it comes pre-installed on almost eighty percent of Smartphones sold, Android has the second largest user base, and increasing.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Direct3D is freely available from Microsoft, as are the rest of the DirectX APIs.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Microsoft developed DirectX for game programmers and continues to add features to the API.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] The DirectX specification is not controlled by an open arbitration committee and Microsoft is free to add, remove or change features.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Direct3D is not portable; it is designed specifically for Microsoft Windows and no other platform (though a form of Direct3D is used on Microsoft's Xbox, Windows Phone 7.5 smartphones and mobile devices which run the Pocket PC operating system).
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Code written with OpenGL is easily ported between platforms with a compatible implementation.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] For example, *Quake II*, which uses OpenGL, was ported from Windows to Linux by a fan of the game.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] OpenGL is a standard maintained by the OpenGL Architecture Review Board (ARB).
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] The ARB meets periodically to update the standard by adding emerging support for features of the latest 3D hardware.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] In addition, the development tools provided by the manufacturers of some video game consoles (such as the Nintendo GameCube, the Nintendo DS, and the PSP) use graphic APIs that resemble OpenGL.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] OpenGL often lags behind on feature updates due to the lack of a permanent development team and the requirement that implementations begin development after the standard has been published.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Programmers who choose to use it can access some hardware's latest 3D features, but only through non-standardized extensions.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] The situation may change in the future as the OpenGL architecture review board (ARB) has passed control of the specification to the Khronos Group in an attempt to counter the problem.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] For development on Microsoft Windows, the various APIs of DirectX may be used for input, sound effects, music, networking and the playback of videos.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Many commercial libraries are available to accomplish these tasks, but since DirectX is available for free, it is the most widely used.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] For console programming, the console manufacturers provide facilities for rendering graphics and the other tasks of game development.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] The console manufacturers also provide complete development systems, without which one cannot legally market nor develop games for their system.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Third-party developers also sell toolkits or libraries that ease the development on one or more of these tasks or provide special benefits, such as cross-platform development capabilities.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] The central component of any game, from a programming standpoint, is the *game loop*.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] The game loop allows the game to run smoothly regardless of a user's input or lack thereof.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Most traditional software programs respond to user input and do nothing without it.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] For example, a word processor formats words and text as a user types.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] If the user doesn't type anything, the word processor does nothing.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Some functions may take a long time to complete, but all are initiated by a user telling the program to do something.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Games, on the other hand, must continue to operate *regardless* of a user's input.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] The loop may be refined and modified as game development progresses, but most games are based on this basic idea.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Game loops differ depending on the platform they are developed for.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] For example, games written for DOS and many consoles can dominate and exploit available processing resources without restraint.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] However, games for a modern PC operating system such as Microsoft Windows must operate within the constraints of the process scheduler.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Some modern games run multiple threads so that, for example, the computation of character AI can be decoupled from the generation of smooth motion within the game.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] This has the disadvantage of (slightly) increased overhead, but the game may run more smoothly and efficiently on hyper-threading or multicore processors and on multiprocessor platforms.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] With the computer industry's focus on CPUs with more cores that can execute more threads, this is becoming increasingly important.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Consoles like the Xbox 360 and PlayStation 3 already have more than one core per processor, and execute more than one thread per core.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] The only platforms widely available for hobbyists to program are consumer operating systems, such as Android, iOS, Windows, Mac, Linux, etc.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] This is because development on game consoles requires special development systems that cost thousands of dollars.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Often these must be obtained from the console manufacturer and are only sold or leased to professional game development studios.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] However, Microsoft used to distribute a game development framework, XNA, which runs on both Microsoft Windows and Xbox 360.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] XNA was discontinued, but other projects like MonoGame and SharpDX are trying to allow the same access for game coding.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Some hobbyists also develop homebrew games, especially for handheld systems or modded consoles.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Some software engineering students program games as exercises for learning a programming language or operating system.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/game-programming] Some hobbyists may use software packages that help with game development, such as Adobe Animate, Unity, Android Studio, pygame, Adventure Game Studio, Roblox Studio, GameMaker Studio, Godot, Unreal Engine, Pixel Game Maker MV, or Construct.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/latest-bevy] Bevy is an open-source, modular game engine built in Rust, with a focus on developer productivity and performance.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/latest-bevy] Check out the Bevy website for more information, read the Quick Start Guide for a step-by-step introduction, and engage with our community if you have any questions or ideas!
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/latest-bevy] Don’t let the simplicity of the example above fool you.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/latest-bevy] Bevy is a fully featured game engine, and it gets more powerful every day!
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/latest-bevy] The `bevy` crate is a container crate that makes it easier to consume Bevy subcrates.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/latest-bevy] The defaults provide a “full engine” experience, but you can easily enable or disable features in your project’s `Cargo.toml` to meet your specific needs.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/latest-bevy] See Bevy’s `Cargo.toml` for a full list of available features.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/latest-bevy] If you prefer, you can also use the individual Bevy crates directly.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/latest-bevy] Each module in the root of this crate, except for the prelude, can be found on crates.io with `bevy_` appended to the front, e.g., `app` -> `bevy_app`.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/latest-bevy] Bevy exposes many Cargo features to customize the engine.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/latest-bevy] Enabling them adds functionality but may come at the cost of longer compilation times and extra dependencies.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/latest-bevy] “Profiles” are high-level groups of cargo features that provide the full Bevy experience, but scoped to a specific domain.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/latest-bevy] These exist to be paired with `default-features = false`, enabling compiling only the subset of Bevy that you need.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/latest-bevy] This can cut down compile times and shrink your final binary size.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/latest-bevy] By default, the `bevy` crate enables the features.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/latest-bevy] “Collections” are mid-level groups of cargo features.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/latest-bevy] These are used to compose the high-level “profiles”.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/latest-bevy] If the default profiles don’t suit your use case (ex: you want to use a custom renderer, you want to build a “headless” app, you want to target no_std, etc), then you can use these collections to build your own “profile” equivalent, without needing to manually manage *every single* feature.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/latest-bevy] This crate is about everything concerning the highest-level, application layer of a Bevy app.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/latest-bevy] In the context of game development, an “asset” is a piece of content that is loaded from disk and displayed in the game.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/latest-bevy] Typically, these are authored by artists and designers (in contrast to code), are relatively large in size, and include everything from textures and models to sounds and music to levels and scripts.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/latest-bevy] A home for first-party camera controllers for Bevy, used for moving the camera around your scene.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/latest-bevy] This crate provides a platform-agnostic interface for accessing the clipboard.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/latest-bevy] Representations of colors in various color spaces.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/latest-bevy] , focused on improving developer experience.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/latest-bevy] It allows users to easily add diagnostic functionality to their Bevy applications, enhancing their ability to monitor and optimize their games.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/latest-bevy] is a collection of styled and themed widgets for building editors and inspectors.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/latest-bevy] Systems and type definitions for gamepad handling in Bevy.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/latest-bevy] This crate adds an immediate mode drawing api to Bevy for visual debugging.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/latest-bevy] and type definitions for loading glTF 2.0 (a standard 3D scene definition format) files in Bevy.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/latest-bevy] The Bevy game engine’s GPU-oriented image type.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/latest-bevy] Provides component types for lighting a bevy scene.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/latest-bevy] This includes the usual directional, point, and spot lights, as well as light probes, atmosphere, other volumetrics, and shadow configuration.
