[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust supports multiple programming paradigms.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] It was influenced by ideas from functional programming, including immutability, higher-order functions, algebraic data types, and pattern matching.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] It also supports object-oriented programming via structs, enums, traits, and methods.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust enforces memory safety (i.e., that all references point to valid memory) without a conventional garbage collector; instead, memory safety errors and data races are prevented by the "borrow checker", which tracks the object lifetime of references at compile time.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Software developer Graydon Hoare created Rust in 2006 while working at Mozilla, which officially sponsored the project in 2009.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The first stable release, Rust 1.0, was published in May 2015.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The project has been sponsored by the Rust Foundation since February 2021.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust has been adopted by many software projects, especially web services and system software.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] It has been studied academically and has a growing community of developers.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust began as a personal project by Mozilla employee Graydon Hoare in 2006.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] According to *MIT Technology Review*, he started the project due to his frustration with a broken elevator in his apartment building whose software had crashed, and named the language after the group of fungi of the same name that is "over-engineered for survival".
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] During the time period between 2006 and 2009, Rust was not publicized to others at Mozilla and was written in Hoare's free time; Hoare began speaking about the language around 2009 after a small group at Mozilla became interested in the project.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Hoare cited languages from the 1970s, 1980s, and 1990s as influences — including CLU, BETA, Mesa, NIL, Erlang, Newsqueak, Napier, Hermes, Sather, Alef, and Limbo.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] During the early years, the Rust compiler was written in about 38,000 lines of OCaml.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Early Rust contained several features no longer present today, including explicit object-oriented programming via an `obj` keyword and a typestates system for variable state changes, such as going from uninitialized to initialized.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Mozilla officially sponsored the Rust project in 2009.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Brendan Eich and other executives, intrigued by the possibility of using Rust for a safe web browser engine, placed engineers on the project including Patrick Walton, Niko Matsakis, Felix Klock, and Manish Goregaokar.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] A conference room taken by the project developers was dubbed "the nerd cave," with a sign placed outside the door.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] During this time period, work had shifted from the initial OCaml compiler to a self-hosting compiler (*i.e.*, written in Rust) targeting LLVM.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The ownership system was in place by 2010.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust logo was developed in 2011 based on a bicycle chainring.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust 0.1 became the first public release on January 20, 2012 for Windows, Linux, and MacOS.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The early 2010s witnessed increasing involvement from full-time engineers at Mozilla and open source volunteers outside Mozilla.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The years from 2012 to 2015 were marked by substantial changes to the Rust type system.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory management through the ownership system was gradually consolidated and expanded.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] By 2013, the garbage collector was rarely used, and was removed in favor of the ownership system.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Other features were removed in order to simplify the language, including typestates, the `pure` keyword, various specialized pointer types, and syntax support for channels.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] According to Steve Klabnik, Rust was influenced during this period by developers coming from C++ (e.g., low-level performance of features), scripting languages (e.g., Cargo and package management), and functional programming (e.g., type systems development).
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Graydon Hoare stepped down from Rust in 2013.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] After Hoare's departure, it evolved organically under a federated governance structure, with a "core team" of initially six people, and around 30-40 developers total across various other teams.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] A Request for Comments (RFC) process for new language features was added in March 2014.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The core team would grow to nine people by 2016 with over 1600 RFCs.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Dobb's Journal* in January 2014, while Rust was "widely viewed as a remarkably elegant language", adoption slowed because it radically changed from version to version.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust development at this time focused on finalizing features for version 1.0 so that it could begin promising backward compatibility.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Six years after Mozilla's sponsorship, Rust 1.0 was published and became the first stable release on May 15, 2015.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] A year later, the Rust compiler had accumulated over 1,400 contributors, and there were over 5,000 third-party libraries published on the Rust package management website Crates.io.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The development of the Servo browser engine continued in parallel with Rust, jointly funded by Mozilla and Samsung.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The teams behind the two projects worked in close collaboration; new features in Rust were tested out by the Servo team, and new features in Servo were used to give feedback back to the Rust team.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The first version of Servo was released in 2016.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The Firefox web browser shipped with Rust code as of 2016 (version 45), but components of Servo did not appear in Firefox until September 2017 (version 57) as part of the Gecko and Quantum projects.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Improvements were made to the Rust toolchain ecosystem during the years following 1.0 including Rustfmt, integrated development environment integration, and a regular compiler testing and release cycle.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's community gained a code of conduct and an IRC chat for discussion.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The earliest known adoption outside of Mozilla was by individual projects at Samsung, Facebook (now Meta Platforms), Dropbox, and Tilde, Inc., the company behind ember.js.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Engineers cited performance, lack of a garbage collector, safety, and pleasantness of working in the language as reasons for the adoption.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Amazon developers cited a finding by Portuguese researchers that Rust code used less energy compared to similar code written in Java.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] In August 2020, Mozilla laid off 250 of its 1,000 employees worldwide, as part of a corporate restructuring caused by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The event raised concerns about the future of Rust.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] In the following week, the Rust Core Team acknowledged the severe impact of the layoffs and announced that plans for a Rust foundation were underway.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The first goal of the foundation would be to take ownership of all trademarks and domain names and to take financial responsibility for their costs.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] On February 8, 2021, the formation of the Rust Foundation was announced by five founding companies: Amazon Web Services, Google, Huawei, Microsoft, and Mozilla.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The foundation would provide financial support for Rust developers in the form of grants and server funding.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] In a blog post published on April 6, 2021, Google announced support for Rust within the Android Open Source Project as an alternative to C/C++.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] On November 22, 2021, the Moderation Team, which was responsible for enforcing the community code of conduct, announced their resignation "in protest of the Core Team placing themselves unaccountable to anyone but themselves".
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] In May 2022, members of the Rust leadership council posted a public response to the incident.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust Foundation posted a draft for a new trademark policy on April 6, 2023, which resulted in widespread negative reactions from Rust users and contributors.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The trademark policy included rules for how the Rust logo and name could be used.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's syntax is similar to that of C and C++, although many of its features were influenced by functional programming languages such as OCaml.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Hoare has described Rust as targeted at frustrated C++ developers.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Below is a "Hello, World!" program in Rust.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The `fn` keyword denotes a function, and the `println!` macro (see § Macros) prints the message to standard output.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Statements in Rust are separated by semicolons.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Variables in Rust are defined through the `let` keyword.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The example below assigns a value to the variable with name `foo` of type `i32` and outputs its value; the type annotation `: i32` can be omitted.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Variables are immutable by default, unless the `mut` keyword is added.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The following example uses `//`, which denotes the start of a comment.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Multiple `let` expressions can define multiple variables with the same name, known as variable shadowing.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Variable shadowing allows transforming variables without having to name the variables differently.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Variable shadowing is also possible for values of different types.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] A *block expression* is delimited by curly brackets.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] An `if` conditional expression executes code based on whether the given value is `true`.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] `else` can be used for when the value evaluates to `false`, and `else if` can be used for combining multiple expressions.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] `while` can be used to repeat a block of code while a condition is met.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] For loops in Rust loop over elements of a collection.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] `for` expressions work over any iterator type.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] In the above code, `4..=10` is a value of type `Range` which implements the `Iterator` trait.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The code within the curly braces is applied to each element returned by the iterator.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Iterators can be combined with functions over iterators like `map`, `filter`, and `sum`.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] More generally, the `loop` keyword allows repeating a portion of code until a `break` occurs.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] `break` may optionally exit the loop with a value.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] In the case of nested loops, labels denoted by `'label_name` can be used to break an outer loop rather than the innermost loop.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The `match` and `if let` expressions can be used for pattern matching.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust is strongly typed and statically typed, meaning that the types of all variables must be known at compilation time.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Assigning a value of a particular type to a differently typed variable causes a compilation error.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Type inference is used to determine the type of variables if unspecified.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The type `()`, called the "unit type" in Rust, is a concrete type that has exactly one value.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] It occupies no memory (as it represents the absence of value).
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] All functions that do not have an indicated return type implicitly return `()`.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] It is similar to `void` in other C-style languages; however, `void` denotes the absence of a type and cannot have any value.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The default integer type is `i32`, and the default floating point type is `f64`.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] If the type of a literal number is not explicitly provided, it is either inferred from the context or the default type is used.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Integer types in Rust are named based on the signedness and the number of bits the type takes.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] For example, `i32` is a signed integer that takes 32 bits of storage, whereas `u8` is unsigned and only takes 8 bits of storage.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] `isize` and `usize` take storage depending on the memory address bus width of the compilation target.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] For example, when building for 32-bit targets, both types will take up 32 bits of space.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, integer literals are in base-10, but different radices are supported with prefixes, for example, `0b11` for binary numbers, `0o567` for octals, and `0xDB` for hexadecimals.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, integer literals default to `i32` as its type.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Suffixes such as `4u32` can be used to explicitly set the type of a literal.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Byte literals such as `b'X'` are available to represent the ASCII value (as a `u8`) of a specific character.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The Boolean type is referred to as `bool` which can take a value of either `true` or `false`.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] A `char` takes up 32 bits of space and represents a Unicode scalar value: a Unicode codepoint that is not a surrogate.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] IEEE 754 floating point numbers are supported with `f32` for single precision floats and `f64` for double precision floats.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Compound types can contain multiple values.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Tuples are fixed-size lists that can contain values whose types can be different.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Arrays are fixed-size lists whose values are of the same type.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's ownership system consists of rules that ensure memory safety without using a garbage collector.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] At compile time, each value must be attached to a variable called the *owner* of that value, and every value must have exactly one owner.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Values are moved between different owners through assignment or passing a value as a function parameter.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Values can also be *borrowed,* meaning they are temporarily passed to a different function before being returned to the owner.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Because of these ownership rules, Rust types are known as *affine types*, meaning each value may be used at most once.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] This enforces a form of software fault isolation as the owner of a value is solely responsible for its correctness and deallocation.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] When a value goes out of scope, it is *dropped* by running its destructor.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The destructor may be programmatically defined through implementing the `Drop` trait.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] This helps manage resources such as file handles, network sockets, and locks, since when objects are dropped, the resources associated with them are closed or released automatically.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Object lifetime refers to the period of time during which a reference is valid; that is, the time between the object creation and destruction.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] These *lifetimes* are implicitly associated with all Rust reference types.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] While often inferred, they can also be indicated explicitly with named lifetime parameters (often denoted `'a`, `'b`, and so on).
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] A value's lifetime in Rust is inferred from the set of locations in the source code (i.e., function, line, and column numbers) for which a variable is valid.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] For example, a reference to a local variable has a lifetime from the expression it is declared in up until the last use of it.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The borrow checker in the Rust compiler then enforces that references are only used in the locations of the source code where the associated lifetime is valid.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] In the example above, storing a reference to variable `x` in `r` is valid, as variable `x` has a longer lifetime (`'a`) than variable `r` (`'b`).
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Since the lifetime of the referenced variable (`'b`) is shorter than the lifetime of the variable holding the reference (`'a`), the borrow checker errors, preventing `x` from being used from outside its scope.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Lifetimes can be indicated using explicit *lifetime parameters* on function arguments.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] In the compiler, ownership and lifetimes work together to prevent memory safety issues such as dangling pointers.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] User-defined types are created with the `struct` or `enum` keywords.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The `struct` keyword is used to denote a record type that groups multiple related values.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] `enum`s can take on different variants at runtime, with their capabilities similar to algebraic data types found in functional programming languages.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Both records and enum variants can contain fields with different types.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Alternative names, or aliases, for the same type can be defined with the `type` keyword.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The `impl` keyword can define methods for a user-defined type.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Data and functions are defined separately.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Implementations fulfill a role similar to that of classes within other languages.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust standard library defines and implements many widely used custom data types, including core data structures such as `Vec`, `Option`, and `HashMap`, as well as smart pointer types.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust provides a way to exclude most of the standard library using the attribute `#![no_std]`, for applications such as embedded devices.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Internally, the standard library is divided into three parts, `core`, `alloc`, and `std`, where `std` and `alloc` are excluded by `#![no_std]`.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Similarly, Rust's result type `Result<T, E>` holds either a successfully computed value (the `Ok` variant) or an error (the `Err` variant).
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Like `Option`, the use of `Result` means that the inner value cannot be used directly; programmers must use a `match` expression, syntactic sugar such as `?` (the "try" operator), or an explicit `unwrap` assertion to access it.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Both `Option` and `Result` are used throughout the standard library and are a fundamental part of Rust's explicit approach to handling errors and missing data.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The `&` and `&mut` reference types are guaranteed to not be null and point to valid memory.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The raw pointer types `*const` and `*mut` opt out of the safety guarantees, thus they may be null or invalid; however, it is impossible to dereference them unless the code is explicitly declared unsafe through the use of an `unsafe` block.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Unlike dereferencing, the creation of raw pointers is allowed inside safe Rust code.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust provides no implicit type conversion (coercion) between most primitive types.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] But, explicit type conversion (casting) can be performed using the `as` keyword.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust supports polymorphism through traits, generic functions, and trait objects.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The example above includes a method `is_zero` which provides a default implementation that may be overridden when implementing the trait.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] In the examples above, `Num: Zero` as well as `where Self: PartialEq` are trait bounds that constrain the type to only allow types that implement `Zero` or `PartialEq`.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Within a trait or impl, `Self` refers to the type that the code is implementing.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Generics can be used in functions to allow implementing a behavior for different types without repeating the same code (see bounded parametric polymorphism).
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Generic functions can be written in relation to other generics, without knowing the actual type.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, traits use static dispatch: the compiler monomorphizes the function for each concrete type instance, yielding performance equivalent to type-specific code at the cost of longer compile times and larger binaries.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] When the exact type is not known at compile time, Rust provides trait objects `&dyn Trait` and `Box<dyn Trait>`.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Trait object calls use dynamic dispatch via a lookup table; a trait object is a "fat pointer" carrying both a data pointer and a method table pointer.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] This indirection adds a small runtime cost, but it keeps a single copy of the code and reduces binary size.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Only "object-safe" traits are eligible to be used as trait objects.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] This approach is similar to duck typing, where all data types that implement a given trait can be treated as functionally interchangeable.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] If an element in the list does not implement the `Display` trait, it will cause a compile-time error.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory and other resources are instead managed through the "resource acquisition is initialization" convention, with optional reference counting.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust provides deterministic management of resources, with very low overhead.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Values are allocated on the stack by default, and all dynamic allocations must be explicit.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The built-in reference types using the `&` symbol do not involve run-time reference counting.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The safety and validity of the underlying pointers are verified at compile time, preventing dangling pointers and other forms of undefined behavior.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's type system separates shared, immutable references of the form `&T` from unique, mutable references of the form `&mut T`.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] A mutable reference can be coerced to an immutable reference, but not vice versa.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's memory safety checks (See #Safety) may be circumvented through the use of `unsafe` blocks.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] This allows programmers to dereference arbitrary raw pointers, call external code, or perform other low-level functionality not allowed by safe Rust.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Some low-level functionality enabled in this way includes volatile memory access, architecture-specific intrinsics, type punning, and inline assembly.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Unsafe code is needed, for example, in the implementation of data structures.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] A frequently cited example is that it is difficult or impossible to implement doubly linked lists in safe Rust.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Programmers using unsafe Rust are considered responsible for upholding Rust's memory and type safety requirements, for example, that no two mutable references exist pointing to the same location.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] If programmers write code that violates these requirements, this results in undefined behavior.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust documentation includes a list of behaviors considered undefined, including accessing dangling or misaligned pointers, or breaking the aliasing rules for references.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Macros allow the generation and transformation of Rust code to reduce repetition.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Macros come in two forms, with *declarative macros* defined through `macro_rules!`, and *procedural macros*, which are defined in separate crates.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] A declarative macro (also called a "macro by example") is a macro, defined using the `macro_rules!` keyword, that uses pattern matching to determine its expansion.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] In this example, the macro named `sum` is defined using the form `macro_rules! sum {` `(...) => { ... } }`.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The first part inside the parentheses of the definition, the macro pattern `( $initial:expr $(, $expr:expr )* $(,)? )` specifies the structure of input it can take.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Here, `$initial:expr` represents the first expression, while `$(, $expr:expr )*` means there can be zero or more additional comma-separated expressions after it.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The trailing `$(,)?` allows the caller to optionally include a final comma without causing an error.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The second part, after the arrow `=>`, describes what code will be generated when the macro is invoked.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] In this case, `$initial $(+ $expr)*` means that the generated code will start with the first expression, followed by a `+` and each of the additional expressions in sequence.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The `*` again means "repeat this pattern zero or more times".
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] This means, when the macro is later called in line 8, as `sum!(1, 2, 3)`, the macro will resolve to `1 + 2 + 3` representing the addition of all of the passed expressions.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Procedural macros are Rust functions that run and modify the compiler's input token stream, before any other components are compiled.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] They are generally more flexible than declarative macros, but are more difficult to maintain due to their complexity.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust supports the creation of foreign function interfaces (FFI) through the `extern` keyword.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] A function that uses the C calling convention can be written using `extern "C" fn`.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The `#[repr(C)]` attribute enables deterministic memory layouts for `struct`s and `enum`s for use across FFI boundaries.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] External libraries such as `bindgen` and `cxx` can generate Rust bindings for C/C++.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Safety properties guaranteed by Rust include memory safety, type safety, and data race freedom.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] As described above, these guarantees can be circumvented by using the `unsafe` keyword.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory safety includes the absence of dereferences to null, dangling, and misaligned pointers, and the absence of buffer overflows and double free errors.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory leaks may occur as a result of creating reference-counted pointers that point at each other (a reference cycle) or can be deliberately created through calling `Box::leak`.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust ecosystem includes its compiler, its standard library, and additional components for software development.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Component installation is typically managed by `rustup`, a Rust toolchain installer developed by the Rust project.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust compiler, `rustc`, compiles Rust code into binaries.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] First, the compiler parses the source code into an AST.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The compiler backend is then invoked as a subcomponent to apply optimizations and translate the resulting IR into object code.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Finally, a linker is used to combine the object(s) into a single executable image.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] rustc uses LLVM as its compiler backend by default, but it also supports using alternative backends such as GCC and Cranelift.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The intention of those alternative backends is to increase platform coverage of Rust or to improve compilation times.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Cargo is Rust's build system and package manager.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] It downloads, compiles, distributes, and uploads packages—called *crates*—that are maintained in an official registry.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] It also acts as a front-end for Clippy and other Rust components.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, Cargo sources its dependencies from the user-contributed registry *crates.io*, but Git repositories, crates in the local filesystem, and other external sources can also be specified as dependencies.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Cargo supports reproducible builds through two metadata files: Cargo.toml and Cargo.lock.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Cargo.toml declares each package used and their version requirements.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Cargo.lock is generated automatically during dependency resolution and records exact versions of all dependencies, including transitive dependencies.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] It formats whitespace and indentation to produce code in accordance with a common style, unless otherwise specified.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] It can be invoked as a standalone program or from a Rust project through Cargo.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Clippy is Rust's built-in linting tool to improve the correctness, performance, and readability of Rust code.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Following Rust 1.0, new features are developed in *nightly* versions, which are released daily.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] During each six-week release cycle, changes to nightly versions are released to beta, while changes from the previous beta version are released to a new stable version.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Every two or three years, a new "edition" is produced.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Editions are released to allow making limited breaking changes, such as promoting `await` to a keyword to support async/await features.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Crates targeting different editions can interoperate with each other, so a crate can upgrade to a new edition even if its callers or its dependencies still target older editions.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Migration to a new edition can be assisted with automated tooling.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Since it performs no garbage collection, Rust is often faster than other memory-safe languages.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Most of Rust's memory safety guarantees impose no runtime overhead, with the notable exception of array indexing which is checked at runtime by default.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The performance impact of array indexing bounds checks varies, but can be significant in some cases.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Many of Rust's features are so-called *zero-cost abstractions*, meaning they are optimized away at compile time and incur no runtime penalty.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The ownership and borrowing system permits zero-copy implementations for some performance-sensitive tasks, such as parsing.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Static dispatch is used by default to eliminate method calls, except for methods called on dynamic trait objects.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The compiler uses inline expansion to eliminate function calls and statically dispatched method invocations.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Unlike C and C++, Rust allows the compiler to reorder struct and enum elements unless a `#[repr(C)]` representation attribute is applied.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] This allows the compiler to produce more efficient code in some cases.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Performance improvements in LLVM carry over to Rust.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] In web services, OpenDNS, a DNS resolution service owned by Cisco, uses Rust internally.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Amazon Web Services uses Rust in "performance-sensitive components" of services.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] In 2019, AWS open-sourced Firecracker, a virtualization solution primarily written in Rust.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Microsoft Azure IoT Edge, a platform used to run Azure services on IoT devices, has components implemented in Rust.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Microsoft also uses Rust to run containerized modules with WebAssembly and Kubernetes.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Cloudflare, a company providing content delivery network services, used Rust to build a new web proxy named Pingora for increased performance and efficiency.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The npm package manager used Rust for its production authentication service in 2019.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] In operating systems, the Linux kernel began introducing experimental support for Rust code in Version 6.1 in late 2022, as part of the Rust for Linux project.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The first drivers written in Rust were included in version 6.8.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] In 2025, kernel developers at the Linux Kernel Developers Summit determined the project to be a success, and Rust usage for kernel code will no longer be considered experimental.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The Android developers used Rust in 2021 to rewrite existing components.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Microsoft has rewritten parts of Windows in Rust.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The r9 project aims to re-implement Plan 9 from Bell Labs in Rust.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust has also been used in the development of new operating systems such as Redox, a "Unix-like" operating system and microkernel, Theseus, an experimental operating system with modular state management, and most of Fuchsia.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust is used for command-line tools and operating system components such as stratisd, a file system manager and COSMIC, a desktop environment by System76.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] In web development, Deno, a secure runtime for JavaScript and TypeScript, is built on top of V8 using Rust and Tokio.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Other notable adoptions in this space include Ruffle, an open-source SWF emulator, and Polkadot, an open source blockchain and cryptocurrency platform.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Components from the Servo browser engine (funded by Mozilla and Samsung) were incorporated in the Gecko browser engine underlying Firefox.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] In January 2023, Google (Alphabet) announced support for using third party Rust libraries in Chromium.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] In other uses, Discord, an instant messaging software company, rewrote parts of its system in Rust for increased performance in 2020.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] In the same year, Dropbox announced that its file synchronization had been rewritten in Rust.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Facebook (Meta) used Rust to redesign its system that manages source code for internal projects.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] In the 2025 Stack Overflow Developer Survey, 14.8% of respondents had recently done extensive development in Rust.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The survey named Rust the "most admired programming language" annually from 2016 to 2025 (inclusive), as measured by the number of existing developers interested in continuing to work in the language.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] In 2025, 29.2% of developers not currently working in Rust expressed an interest in doing so.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's safety and performance have been investigated in programming languages research.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] In other fields, a journal article published to *Proceedings of the International Astronomical Union* used Rust to simulate multi-planet systems.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] An article published in *Nature* shared stories of bioinformaticians using Rust.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Both articles cited Rust's performance and safety as advantages, and the learning curve as being a primary drawback to Rust adoption.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The 2025 DARPA project TRACTOR aims to automatically translate C to Rust using techniques such as static analysis, dynamic analysis, and large language models.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] According to the *MIT Technology Review*, the Rust community has been seen as "unusually friendly" to newcomers and particularly attracted people from the queer community, partly due to its code of conduct.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] Inclusiveness has been cited as an important factor for some Rust developers.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The official Rust blog collects and publishes demographic data each year.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The **Rust Foundation** is a non-profit membership organization incorporated in United States; it manages the Rust trademark, infrastructure, and assets.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] It was established on February 8, 2021, with five founding corporate members (Amazon Web Services, Huawei, Google, Microsoft, and Mozilla).
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The foundation's board was chaired by Shane Miller, with Ashley Williams as interim executive director.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] In late 2021, Rebecca Rumbul became executive director and CEO.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust project is maintained by 8 top-level *teams* as of November 2025: the leadership council, compiler team, dev tools team, infrastructure team, language team, launching pad, library team, and moderation team.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/rust-programming-language] The leadership council oversees the project and is formed by representatives among the other teams.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] A **scene graph** is a hierarchical data structure commonly used by vector-based graphics editing applications and modern computer games, which cascades the inheritance or spatial representation of a set of objects.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] It is a collection of nodes in a graph or tree structure.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] A tree node may have many children but only a single parent, with the effect of a parent applied to all its child nodes; an operation performed on a group automatically propagates its effect to all of its members.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] In many programs, associating a geometrical transformation matrix (see also transformation and matrix) at each group level and concatenating such matrices together is an efficient and natural way to process such operations.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] A common feature, for instance, is the ability to group related shapes and objects into a compound object that can then be manipulated as easily as a single object.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] In vector-based graphics editing, each leaf node in a scene graph represents some atomic unit of the document, usually a shape such as an ellipse or Bezier path.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] Although shapes themselves (particularly paths) can be decomposed further into nodes such as spline nodes, it is practical to think of the scene graph as composed of shapes rather than going to a lower level of representation.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] Another useful and user-driven node concept is the layer.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] A layer acts like a transparent sheet upon which any number of shapes and shape groups can be placed.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] The document then becomes a set of layers, any of which can be conveniently made invisible, dimmed, or locked (made read-only).
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] Some applications place all layers in a linear list, while others support layers within layers to any desired depth.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] Internally, there may be no real structural difference between layers and groups at all, since they are both just nodes of a scene graph.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] If differences are needed, a common type declaration in C++ would be to make a generic node class, and then derive layers and groups as subclasses.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] A visibility member, for example, would be a feature of a layer, but not necessarily of a group.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] Scene graphs are useful for modern games using 3D graphics and increasingly large worlds or levels.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] In such applications, nodes in a scene graph (generally) represent entities or objects in the scene.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] For instance, a game might define a logical relationship between a knight and a horse so that the knight is considered an extension to the horse.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] The scene graph would have a 'horse' node with a 'knight' node attached to it.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] The scene graph may also describe the spatial, as well as the logical, relationship of the various entities: the knight moves through 3D space as the horse moves.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] In these large applications, memory requirements are major considerations when designing a scene graph.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] For this reason, many large scene graph systems use geometry instancing to reduce memory costs and increase speed.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] In our example above, each knight is a separate scene node, but the graphical representation of the knight (made up of a 3D mesh, textures, materials and shaders) is instanced.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] This means that only a single copy of the data is kept, which is then referenced by any 'knight' nodes in the scene graph.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] This allows a reduced memory budget and increased speed, since when a new knight node is created, the appearance data need not be duplicated.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] The simplest form of scene graph uses an array or linked list data structure, and displaying its shapes is simply a matter of linearly iterating the nodes one by one.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] Other common operations, such as checking to see which shape intersects the mouse pointer are also done via linear searches.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] For small scene graphs, this tends to suffice.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] Applying an operation on a scene graph requires some way of dispatching an operation based on a node's type.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] For example, in a render operation, a transformation group node would accumulate its transformation by matrix multiplication, vector displacement, quaternions or Euler angles.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] After which a leaf node sends the object off for rendering to the renderer.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] Some implementations might render the object directly, which invokes the underlying rendering API, such as DirectX or OpenGL.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] But since the underlying implementation of the rendering API usually lacks portability, one might separate the scene graph and rendering systems instead.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] In order to accomplish this type of dispatching, several different approaches can be taken.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] In object-oriented languages such as C++, this can easily be achieved by virtual functions, where each represents an operation that can be performed on a node.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] Virtual functions are simple to write, but it is usually impossible to add new operations to nodes without access to the source code.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] Alternatively, the *visitor pattern* can be used.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] This has a similar disadvantage in that it is similarly difficult to add new node types.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] Other techniques involve the use of RTTI (Run-Time Type Information).
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] The operation can be realised as a class that is passed to the current node; it then queries the node's type using RTTI and looks up the correct operation in an array of callbacks or functors.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] This requires that the map of types to callbacks or functors be initialized at runtime, but offers more flexibility, speed and extensibility.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] Variations on these techniques exist, and new methods can offer added benefits.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] One alternative is scene graph rebuilding, where the scene graph is rebuilt for each of the operations performed.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] This, however, can be very slow, but produces a highly optimised scene graph.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] It demonstrates that a good scene graph implementation depends heavily on the application in which it is used.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] Traversals are the key to the power of applying operations to scene graphs.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] At this point, many scene graph engines then traverse back up the tree, applying a similar operation.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] For example, consider a render operation that takes transformations into account: while recursively traversing down the scene graph hierarchy, a pre-render operation is called.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] If the node is a transformation node, it adds its own transformation to the current transformation matrix.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] Once the operation finishes traversing all the children of a node, it calls the node's post-render operation so that the transformation node can undo the transformation.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] This approach drastically reduces the necessary amount of matrix multiplication.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] Some scene graph operations are actually more efficient when nodes are traversed in a different order – this is where some systems implement scene graph rebuilding to reorder the scene graph into an easier-to-parse format or tree.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] For example, in 2D cases, scene graphs typically render themselves by starting at the tree's root node and then recursively draw the child nodes.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] The tree's leaves represent the most foreground objects.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] Since drawing proceeds from back to front with closer objects simply overwriting farther ones, the process is known as employing the Painter's algorithm.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] In 3D systems, which often employ depth buffers, it is more efficient to draw the closest objects first, since farther objects often need only be depth-tested instead of actually rendered, because they are occluded by nearer objects.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] Bounding Volume Hierarchies (BVHs) are useful for numerous tasks – including efficient culling and speeding up collision detection between objects.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] A BVH is a spatial structure, but doesn't have to partition the geometry (see spatial partitioning below).
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] A BVH is a tree of bounding volumes (often spheres, axis-aligned bounding boxes or oriented bounding boxes).
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] At the bottom of the hierarchy, the size of the volume is just large enough to encompass a single object tightly (or possibly even some smaller fraction of an object in high resolution BVHs).
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] As one ascends the hierarchy, each node has its own volume that tightly encompasses all the volumes beneath it.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] At the root of the tree is a volume that encompasses all the volumes in the tree (the whole scene).
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] BVHs are useful for speeding up collision detection between objects.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] If an object's bounding volume does not intersect a volume higher in the tree, it cannot intersect any object below that node (so they are all rejected very quickly).
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] There are some similarities between BVHs and scene graphs.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] A scene graph can easily be adapted to include/become a BVH – if each node has a volume associated or there is a purpose-built "bound node" added in at convenient location in the hierarchy.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] This may not be the typical view of a scene graph, but there are benefits to including a BVH in a scene graph.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] An effective way of combining spatial partitioning and scene graphs is by creating a scene leaf node that contains the spatial partitioning data.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] This can increase computational efficiency of rendering.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] Spatial data is usually static and generally contains non-moving scene data in some partitioned form.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] Some systems may have the systems and their rendering separately.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] This is fine and there are no real advantages to either method.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] In particular, it is bad to have the scene graph contained within the spatial partitioning system, as the scene graph is better thought of as the grander system to the spatial partitioning.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] Very large drawings, or scene graphs that are generated solely at runtime (as happens in ray tracing rendering programs), require defining of group nodes in a more automated fashion.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] A raytracer, for example, will take a scene description of a 3D model and build an internal representation that breaks up its individual parts into bounding boxes (also called bounding slabs).
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] These boxes are grouped hierarchically so that ray intersection tests (as part of visibility determination) can be efficiently computed.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] A group box that does not intersect an eye ray, for example, can entirely skip testing any of its members.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] A similar efficiency holds in 2D applications as well.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] If the user has magnified a document so that only part of it is visible on their computer screen, and then scrolls in it, it is useful to use a bounding box (or in this case, a bounding rectangle scheme) to quickly determine which scene graph elements are visible and thus actually need to be drawn.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] Depending on the particulars of the application's drawing performance, a large part of the scene graph's design can be impacted by rendering efficiency considerations.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] In 3D video games such as Quake, binary space partitioning (BSP) trees are heavily favored to minimize visibility tests.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] BSP trees, however, take a very long time to compute from design scene graphs, and must be recomputed if the design scene graph changes, so the levels tend to remain static, and dynamic characters aren't generally considered in the spatial partitioning scheme.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] Scene graphs for dense regular objects such as heightfields and polygon meshes tend to employ quadtrees and octrees, which are specialized variants of a 3D bounding box hierarchy.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] Since a heightfield occupies a box volume itself, recursively subdividing this box into eight subboxes (hence the 'oct' in octree) until individual heightfield elements are reached is efficient and natural.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] PHIGS was the first commercial scene graph specification, and became an ANSI standard in 1988.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] Disparate implementations were provided by Unix hardware vendors.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] The HOOPS 3D Graphics System appears to have been the first commercial scene graph library provided by a single software vendor.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] It was designed to run on disparate lower-level 2D and 3D interfaces, with the first major production version (v3.0) completed in 1991.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] Silicon Graphics (SGI) released OpenGL Performer or more commonly called Performer in 1991 which was the primary scenegraph system for most SGI products into the future.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] IRIS Inventor 1.0 (1992) was released by SGI, which was a high level scene graph built on top of Performer.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] It was followed up with Open Inventor in 1994, another iteration of the high level scene graph built on top of newer releases of Performer.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] More 3D scene graph libraries can be found in Category:3D scenegraph APIs.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] X3D is a royalty-free open standards file format and run-time architecture to represent and communicate 3D scenes and objects using XML.
[src:bevy-ecs-rust/scene-graph] It is an ISO-ratified standard that provides a system for the storage, retrieval and playback of real-time graphics content embedded in applications, all within an open architecture to support a wide array of domains and user scenarios.
